  "prompt": "What is the electron configuration of electron?",
  "response": "The electron configuration describes the distribution of electrons in the atomic orbitals of an atom. The specific configuration depends on the element in question. Here are the general steps to determine the electron configuration:\n\n1. **Identify the Atomic Number**: The atomic number (Z) of an element tells you the number of protons and, in a neutral atom, the number of electrons.\n\n2. **Follow the Aufbau Principle**: Electrons fill atomic orbitals starting from the lowest energy level to higher energy levels. The order is:\n   - 1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p, 4s, 3d, 4p, 5s, 4d, 5p, 6s, 4f, 5d, 6p, 7s, 5f, 6d, 7p.\n\n3. **Apply the Pauli Exclusion Principle**: No two electrons can have the same set of quantum numbers; thus, each orbital can hold a maximum of two electrons with opposite spins.\n\n4. **Use Hund's Rule**: Electrons will fill degenerate orbitals (orbitals of the same energy) singly before pairing up.\n\n### Example: Carbon (C)\nAtomic number of carbon is 6. Its electron configuration is:\n- 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u00b2\n\n### Noble Gas Configuration\nFor elements with higher atomic numbers, you can use the noble gas configuration as a shorthand. For example, the electron configuration for sodium (Na) can be written as [Ne] 3s\u00b9, where [Ne] represents the electron configuration of neon (1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2076).\n\n### Specific Example: Oxygen (O)\nAtomic number of oxygen is 8. Its electron configuration is:\n- 1s\u00b2 2s\u00b2 2p\u2074\n\n### Summary\nThe electron configuration of an element is a detailed description of how its electrons are distributed in its atomic orbitals. The configuration follows specific rules and principles, such as the Aufbau principle, the Pauli exclusion principle, and Hund's rule. The exact configuration depends on the element's atomic number.",
